# Code Organization

## Single Responsibility

- One module = one purpose. If a file does two unrelated things, split it.
- Functions under 40 lines; files under 300 lines (guidelines, not hard limits)
- If you need a comment block saying "--- Section X ---", it's a new file

## Directory Convention

```
feature/
  index.ts          → Public API (barrel export)
  feature.ts        → Core logic
  feature.test.ts   → Tests colocated with source
  feature.types.ts  → Types/interfaces (if complex)
  utils.ts          → Feature-specific helpers
```

- Colocate tests, types, and styles with the code they support
- Use barrel exports (`index.ts`) to define what's public; keep internals private

## Import Order

Group imports in this order, separated by blank lines:

1. Node built-ins (`node:fs`, `node:path`)
2. External packages (`react`, `express`)
3. Internal packages (`@org/ui`, `@org/utils`)
4. Relative imports (`./utils`, `../shared`)

## Separation of Concerns

- Business logic must not depend on framework/transport details
- Keep I/O (DB, HTTP, file system) at the edges; core logic stays pure
- Configuration lives in dedicated files — never scatter env reads across modules

## Avoid

```
❌ Circular imports between modules
❌ God files (>500 lines touching multiple domains)
❌ Deeply nested folders (>4 levels) without clear benefit
❌ Re-exporting everything from a package root (barrel bloat)
```
